</details>

---

<details><summary>

#### Declarations diff

</summary>

`+ Complex.integerComplement`
`+ IntegerComplement_eq`
`+ UpperHalfPlane.coe_mem_integerComplement`
`+ closedEmbedding_intCast`
`+ integerComplement.add_coe_int_mem`
`+ integerComplement.mem_iff`
`+ integerComplement.ne_one`
`+ integerComplement.ne_zero`

`+ ne_int`
`+ ne_nat`
<details>

```bash

## more verbose report:

```
</details>

The doc-module for `script/declarations_diff.sh` contains some details about this script.

</details>

So I changed the definition to now make it a `Set ℂ` instead of its own type. Originally I was just following the UpperHalfPlane API, but as @loefflerd points out, this is probably not needed here. But if anyone has a good reason why it should be its own type then I'd be interested to know!

Ok I've added the suggestions from the reviews and I also changed the definition so actually be `(Set.range ((↑) : ℤ → ℂ))ᶜ` since that is what the `IsOpen` lemma is written as. I added some basic lemmas to relate to the previous definition. But I'm happy to change it back if people think this isn't ideal.

:v: CBirkbeck can now approve this pull request. To approve and merge a pull request, simply reply with `bors r+`. More detailed instructions are available [here](https://bors.tech/documentation/getting-started/#reviewing-pull-requests).
bors r+

Pull request successfully merged into master.

Build succeeded:
  * [Lint style](https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/actions/runs/11854455357/job/33036648408)
  * [Build](https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/actions/runs/11854455357/job/33036648057)
bors d+
You'll need to merge master, as some things like `ClosedEmbedding` have been renamed.
Thanks! I've supplied some alternate proofs for you.
bors d+

```suggestion
We also show that the upper half plane embeds into the integer complement.
```
perhaps?

```suggestion
lemma ℂ_ℤ_Isclosed : IsClosed (((↑) : ℤ → ℂ) '' ⊤) := by
```

```suggestion
lemma UpperHalfPlane.ne_int (z : ℍ) : ∀ n : ℤ, z.1 ≠ n := by
```

```suggestion
instance : Coe ℍ ℂ_ℤ := ⟨fun x => ⟨x, by simpa using upper_half_plane_ne_int x⟩⟩
```
Can we give this a name and make this a (scoped) notation? Then you could use it in the names below as well

```suggestion
noncomputable instance : UniformSpace ℂ_ℤ := instUniformSpaceSubtype
```
Please move to `Mathlib.Analysis.Complex.Basic` as `Complex.closedEmbedding_intCast`
Please don't use top for sets, but also it seems like this should use `Set.range` directly. Also, this should move to `Mathlib.Analysis.Complex.Basic` as `Complex.isClosed_range_intCast`

Also move, and I think state as
```lean
lemma Complex.isOpen_compl_range_intCast : IsOpen (Set.range ((↑) : ℤ → ℂ))ᶜ :=
  Complex.isClosed_range_intCast.isOpen_compl 
```

You can just prove
```lean
theorem isometry_intCast : Isometry ((↑) : ℤ → ℂ) := 
  Isometry.of_dist_eq <| by simp_rw [← Complex.ofReal_intCast,
    Complex.isometry_ofReal.dist_eq, Int.dist_cast_real, implies_true]
```
and then get the `ClosedEmbedding` for free.

You might need to write a separate function for this (so that you can mark it `@[coe]`), as I'm not sure that Lean will see through the defeq. At the very least, it's better practice to write a separate function rather than using a defeq-abused `Subtype.val`.
Similarly here, you need to write a separate `@[coe] def foo : ℍ → ℂ_ℤ` for this and then this instance becomes `⟨foo⟩`.
Maybe you want `ℂ_ℤ_not_one` too?
This probably doesn't belong in this file (and maybe you want a version for `ne_nat` too?)
I would be tempted to namespace this as `Complex.IntegerComplement` and then use that in the names instead of `ℂ_ℤ`. We don't use notation in declaration names elsewhere.
This is not needed with the `Set` version
Nor this – better to have a lemma `isOpen_integerComplement`

Keeping track of coercions is already a serious headache in the modular forms code; let's not add even more of them. Why not just `lemma UpperHalfPlane.coe_mem_integerComplement (z : ℍ) : \u z \in ℂ_ℤ`?
I would write the hypotheses as `{x : ℂ} (hx : x \in ℂ_ℤ)` rather than using a subtype
I'm not sure this does anything (declaring an instance on a set rather than a type) – the TC machinery will never look for it.
No it wasnt supposed to be there. I was just testing if apply? would find the result, but forgot to delete it!

This is a set, so it should use `lowerCamelCase`.
```suggestion
abbrev Complex.integerComplement := (Set.range ((↑) : ℤ → ℂ))ᶜ
```
BTW, why do you want to have it reducible?
So I wanted apply? to find the `IsOpen` result for me and it wouldn't if it was a def (unless I was doing the wrong thing).
It should find it if you `rw [Complex.integerComplement]` and then use `apply?`. I suspect you don't want this to be an `abbrev`, but I could be wrong.
Ah yes ok that works. I changed it back to a `def`. But out of curiosity, why do you think we don't want it to be an abbrev? (I dont have much of a feel for these things).
I'm not totally sure that it should be `def` over `abbrev`; it's just my intuition here. I don't think there's anything strong pointing in either direction.

If you turn the equality around (which you *should* do here and elsewhere) this is just `rfl`:
```suggestion
lemma IntegerComplement_eq : ℂ_ℤ = {z : ℂ | ¬ ∃ (n : ℤ), n = z} := rfl
```

Likewise:
```suggestion
lemma IntegerComplement_not_exist {x : ℂ} (hx : x ∈ ℂ_ℤ) : ¬ ∃ (n : ℤ), n = x := hx

lemma IntegerComplement_mk {x : ℂ} (hx : ¬ ∃ (n : ℤ), n = x) : x ∈ ℂ_ℤ := hx
```
But actually, the latter is misnamed now that it's not a subtype. I would probably just turn this into a `rw` lemma like this:
```
lemma integerComplement.mem_iff {x : ℂ} : x ∈ ℂ_ℤ ↔ ¬ ∃ (n : ℤ), n = x := Iff.rfl
```
and then you can add `alias`es if you prefer.

You can have a stronger result here:
```suggestion
lemma integerComplement.add_coe_int_mem {x : ℂ} (a : ℤ) : x + (a : ℂ) ∈ ℂ_ℤ ↔ x ∈ ℂ_ℤ := by
```
And then your original result follows easily from this and the next result.
Sure! although my proof of this is not very pretty, maybe you have some ideas how to golf it? (also is there a contrapose for iffs??)
Done in another suggestion.

I would namespace this, and the new proof avoids the previous lemma.
```suggestion
lemma integerComplement.ne_zero {x : ℂ} (hx : x ∈ ℂ_ℤ) : x ≠ 0 :=
  fun hx' ↦ hx ⟨0, by exact_mod_cast hx'.symm⟩
```

likewise:
```suggestion
lemma integerComplement.ne_one {x : ℂ} (hx : x ∈ ℂ_ℤ): x ≠ 1 :=
  fun hx' ↦ hx ⟨1, by exact_mod_cast hx'.symm⟩
```

```suggestion
lemma UpperHalfPlane.coe_mem_integerComplement (z : ℍ) : ↑z ∈ ℂ_ℤ :=
  not_exists.mpr fun x hx ↦ ne_int z x hx.symm 
```

```suggestion
  simp only [mem_iff, not_iff_not]
  exact ⟨(Exists.elim · fun n hn ↦ ⟨n - a, by simp [hn]⟩),
    (Exists.elim · fun n hn ↦ ⟨n + a, by simp [hn]⟩)⟩
```
or if you prefer it not so heavily golfed:
```suggestion
  simp only [mem_iff, not_iff_not]
  constructor
  · rintro ⟨n, hn⟩
    exact ⟨n - a, by simp [hn]⟩
  · rintro ⟨n, rfl⟩
    exact ⟨n + a, by simp⟩
```
The proof of `UpperHalfPlane.coe_mem_integerComplement` mildly suggests that these lemmas should be turned around, but I'm not going to push for this.
Hmm sure, I'll see if it becomes annoying later on with the use case I have for this, if so I'll come back and change them.

```suggestion
lemma integerComplement_eq : ℂ_ℤ = {z : ℂ | ¬ ∃ (n : ℤ), n = z} := rfl
```
